ce:section.ce:para:
GQDs are newly introduced biocompatible nanoscale materials with the potential of bioimaging and drug delivery. The surface functional groups of the GQDs provide the possibility of their modification with various types of materials like dendrimers. PAMAM is a famous member of the dendrimer family with mono-disperse and highly branched architecture that has been attracted much attention for its use in medicine. Hence, in this work, the GQDs surface was modified PAMAM to reach the new drug delivery system with the advantage of both GQDs and PAMAM. For this aim, GQDs functionalized with APTS and the amine-functionalized GQDs were obtained via silanization (GQDs-NH2, Fig. 1
                     ). Thereafter, in the first step of the dendrimer growth, the GQDs-NH2 was reacted with MA through the Michael addition reaction. The resulting material of the Michael addition reaction denoted as GQDs-PAMAM-G0.5. In the next step, the amidation of ester groups of the GQDs-PAMAM-G0.5 via reaction with EA achieved the GQDs-PAMAM-G1 (See Fig. S1). The following specified generations were obtained as a result of repeating these two steps (Ma, Xing, Shao, Du, & La, 2017; Xiao, Yan, Zeng, & Liu, 2016). It is reported that despite the many benefits of PAMAM, it has some drawbacks, which limit its usage in biomedicine. One of the problems of the PAMAM is its strong positive surface charges within the physiological conditions that lead to its more cell cytotoxicity. The electrostatic interaction of the negatively charged biological lipid bilayer membrane with positively charged amino groups on the surface of the PAMAM dendrimers caused to the cell lysis and is a reason for its more cytotoxicity. For solving this problem, the reaction of the amino groups with appropriate compounds having neutral or anionic functional groups is needed to reduce/shield its positive charges, decrease the electrostatic interaction, and improve its biocompatibility (Luong et al., 2016). Hence, GQDs-PAMAM was functionalized with β-CD as a more biocompatible oligosaccharide with a large number of hydroxyl groups. Functionalization was occurred via the SN2 nucleophilic substitution reaction of the monotosylated βCDs with the amino groups of the dendrimer (See Fig. S2). Scheme 1
                      shows the overall pathway of the GQDs-PAMAM-β-CD glycodendrimer synthesis. The newly prepared photoluminescent GQDs-PAMAM-β-CD glycodendrimer characterized by several techniques and finally evaluated as a DOX delivery nanodevice.
